3️⃣ When to Use Command Pattern

Command Pattern use karo jab:

✔ Undo/Redo functionality chahiye
✔ Task history maintain karni ho
✔ Sender aur Receiver logic separate karna ho
✔ Multiple actions ko queue me schedule karna ho
✔ Behavioral if-else logic ho


4️⃣ Problem Example – Task Scheduler

Suppose aapko ek Task Scheduler banana hai jo:

Email bheje

Report generate kare

Database backup kare

Without any pattern, code aisa dikhega:


public void runTask(String type) {
    if(type.equals("EMAIL")) {
        EmailService email = new EmailService();
        email.sendEmail();
    }
    else if(type.equals("REPORT")) {
        ReportService report = new ReportService();
        report.generateReport();
    }
    else if(type.equals("BACKUP")) {
        BackupService backup = new BackupService();
        backup.backupDatabase();
    }
}

5️⃣ Problems in This Approach
❌ 1. Tight Coupling

Object creation + behavior dono same jagah likha hua hai.

❌ 2. Not Modular

Ek jagah change → pura system impact.

❌ 3. Open Closed Principle Violation

Naya task add karne ke liye class modify karni padegi.

❌ 4. Code Scalability Issue

Code base bada hoga to change risky ho jayega.



7️⃣ Core Idea of Command Pattern

Har task ko ek Command Object bana do.

Har command ke paas 2 methods honge:

execute()
undo()



